<section xml:id="sec_conditional_statements">
  <title>Conditional Statements</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Most statements in mathematics and computer science involve conditionals:
      if one thing happens, then another thing happens.
      Consider, for example,
      a database that tracks patients who have scheduled follow-up visits
      (or not).
      We might want to send a reminder to patients who have not yet scheduled their follow-up visits.
      That is, if the patient has not scheduled their follow-up visit,
      then we want to send them a reminder.
    </p>
    <p>
      In this section,
      we study conditional statements and how to prove that they are true.
      We also look at their negations and construct counterexamples.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_if_then">
    <title>\subifthen</title>
    <p>
      We begin with a definition.
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="defn_conditional">
      <title>Conditional statements</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                For statements <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>, the statement
                <q><term>if</term> <m>P</m>, <term>then</term> <m>Q</m></q>, denoted <m>P \to Q</m>, is a <term>conditional</term> statement.
                We also say <m>P</m> <term>implies</term> <m>Q</m>.
                The statement <m>P \to Q</m> promises that if <m>P</m> is true,
                then <m>Q</m> must also be true.
                For example,
                consider the following statement: For any integer <m>k</m>,
                if <m>k=3</m>, then <m>k^2=9</m>.
                This statement is true because when <m>k=3</m> we have <m>k^2 = 3^2 = 9</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                In the statement <m>P \to Q</m>,
                the statement <m>P</m> is the <term>hypothesis</term>
                and <m>Q</m> is the <term>conclusion</term>.
                For example,
                consider the following statement: If a graph is a tree,
                then it has a leaf.
                The hypothesis is that a graph is a tree.
                The conclusion is that it has a leaf.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
      For <m>P \to Q</m> to be true,
      it must be the case that if <m>P</m> is true,
      then <m>Q</m> is 100% guaranteed to also be true.
      It might be the case that <m>P</m> causes <m>Q</m>, for example,
      if <m>P</m>: Tova dropped her glove in a puddle and <m>Q</m>: Tova's glove got wet. then <m>P \to Q</m>: If Tova dropped her glove in a puddle,
      then Tova's glove got wet. is true.
      In this example, <m>P</m> caused <m>Q</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Alternatively,
      it might be the case that <m>Q</m> had to happen in order for <m>P</m> to happen.
      For example,
      if <m>P</m>: Derek got an A in Algorithms class and <m>Q</m>: Derek took the Algorithms class. then <m>P \to Q</m>:
      if Derek got an A in Algorithms class,
      then Derek took the Algorithms class. is true.
      In this example, <m>Q</m> would have to happen before <m>P</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Let's look more closely at when a conditional is true or false.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_understand_ifthen_true">
      <title>Understanding when a conditional is true</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the following conditional statement <m>S</m>: If you show up to class every day and do all of the homework on time,
        </p>
        <p>
          then you will get an A in this class.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Is <m>S</m> true or false if you show up to class every day and do all of the homework on time and you get an A in this class?
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    It is true.
                    When both the hypothesis and the conclusion are true, we have kept the promise.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Is <m>S</m> true or false if you show up to class every day and do all of the homework on time but you do not get an A in this class?
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    It is false.
                    When the hypothesis is true but the conclusion is false,
                    we have broken the promise.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Is <m>S</m> true or false if I do not always show up to class and do not always get my homework in on time,
                but I still get an A in this class?
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    It is true.
                    When the hypothesis is false but the conclusion is false,
                    we have not broken the promise.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Is <m>S</m> true or false if I do not always show up to class and do not always get my homework in on time and I get a C in this class?
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    It is true.
                    When the hypothesis and the conclusion are false,
                    we have not broken the promise.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      We summarize our analysis from <xref ref="exam_understand_ifthen_true"></xref> using a truth table.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_truthtable_conditionals">
      <title>Truth table for if/then</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Construct a truth table for <m>P \to Q</m>.
        </p>
        <solution>
          <p>
            The truth table is shown in <xref ref="table_truthtable_conditional"></xref>.
          </p>
        </solution>
        <table xml:id="table_truthtable_conditional">
          <title>Truth table for the logical connective <term>implies</term></title>
          <tabular>
            <row>
              <cell><m>P</m></cell>
              <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
              <cell><m>P \to Q</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row bottom="minor">
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
              <cell></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{F}</cell>
              <cell>\str{T}</cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </table>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      It is important to note the case where the hypothesis of a conditional is false.
    </p>
    <remark xml:id="rem_false_implies_is_true">
      <title>False implies anything is true</title>
      <p>
        The statement <m>P \to Q</m> is true when <m>P</m> is false,
        no matter what <m>Q</m> is.
      </p>
    </remark>
    <p>
      Practice working with more complicated conditional statements.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_promises">
      <title>Promises</title>
      <p>
        In many parts of this activity,
        you are asked to construct a truth table.
        You may start a new truth table for each part,
        but consider adding columns to your existing truth table instead.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              Copy the truth table for <m>P \to Q</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Add a column for <m>\neg P</m> and another column for <m>\neg P \to Q</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_truthtable_converse">
            <p>
              Add a column for <m>Q \to P</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_truthtable_simplification">
            <p>
              Use your truth table to show that
              <m>(P \land Q) \to P</m> is a tautology by adding a column for
              <m>P \land Q</m> and another column for <m>(P \land Q) \to P</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_truthtable_implication">
            <p>
              Add a column for <m>\neg P \lor Q</m>.
              What do you notice?
              Discuss why that makes sense.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
      Make sure that you have <xref ref="act_promises">completed</xref>
      because we are about to reveal some of the answers.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_truthtable_compound_conditionals">
      <title>Truth tables for statements involving conditionals</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Construct a truth table for <m>Q \to P</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    <xref ref="table_truthtable_converse"></xref> shows the truth table.
                    Note that the hypothesis is now <m>Q</m> and the conclusion is now <m>P</m>.
                    The only time <m>Q \to P</m> is false is when the hypothesis <m>Q</m> is true but the conclusion <m>P</m> is false.
                  </p>
                  <table xml:id="table_truthtable_converse">
                    <title>Truth table for the converse <m>Q \to P</m></title>
                    <tabular>
                      <row>
                        <cell><m>P</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>Q \to P</m></cell>
                      </row>
                      <row bottom="minor">
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                      </row>
                      <row>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      </row>
                      <row>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      </row>
                      <row>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      </row>
                      <row>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      </row>
                    </tabular>
                  </table>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="part_truthtable_simplification2">
              <p>
                Use a truth table to show that <m>(P \land Q) \to P</m> is a tautology.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    <xref ref="table_truthtable_simplification"></xref> shows the truth table.
                    Because the last column is all true,
                    we can conclude that <m>(P \land Q) \to P</m> is a tautology.
                  </p>
                  <table xml:id="table_truthtable_simplification">
                    <title>Truth table showing the tautology for the simplification inference <m>(P \land Q) \to P</m></title>
                    <tabular>
                      <row>
                        <cell><m>P</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>(P \land Q)</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>(P \land Q) \to P</m></cell>
                      </row>
                      <row bottom="minor">
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                      </row>
                      <row>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      </row>
                      <row>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      </row>
                      <row>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      </row>
                      <row>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      </row>
                    </tabular>
                  </table>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Construct a truth table for <m>\neg P \lor Q</m>.
                What do you notice?
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    <xref ref="table_truthtable_implication"></xref> shows the truth table.
                    Because the last column is the same as the truth table for <m>P \to Q</m> in <xref ref="table_truthtable_conditional"></xref>,
                    we can conclude that they are logically equivalent.
                    That is, <m>\neg P \lor Q \equiv P \to Q</m>.
                  </p>
                  <table xml:id="table_truthtable_implication">
                    <title>Truth table showing the implication equivalence <m>P \to Q \equiv \neg P \lor Q</m></title>
                    <tabular>
                      <row>
                        <cell><m>P</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>Q</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\neg P</m></cell>
                        <cell><m>\neg P \lor Q</m></cell>
                      </row>
                      <row bottom="minor">
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                      </row>
                      <row>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      </row>
                      <row>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                      </row>
                      <row>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      </row>
                      <row>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{F}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                        <cell>\str{T}</cell>
                      </row>
                    </tabular>
                  </table>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      Note the new equivalence we found in <xref ref="act_promises"></xref>
      <xref ref="part_truthtable_implication"/>.
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="thm_implication">
      <title>Implication equivalence</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                For statements <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>,
                <me>
                  P \to Q \equiv \neg P \lor Q
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Equivalently, for statements <m>R</m> and <m>Q</m>,
                <me>
                  R \lor Q \equiv \neg R \to Q
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <p>
      Note that the second statement of <xref ref="thm_implication"></xref>
      follows from the first by substituting
      <m>R = \neg P</m> and therefore <m>P = \neg R</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      A common use of if/then in computer programming is the if/then/else construction.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_if_then_else">
      <title>
      <q>If, then, else</q>
      construction</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          A common command in computer programming is a statement of the form
          <q>If <m>P</m>, then <m>Q</m>, else <m>R</m>.</q>
          This statement tells the computer that if <m>P</m> is true,
          then do what <m>Q</m> says and if <m>P</m> is false,
          then do what <m>R</m> says.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Write the statement if <m>P</m>, then <m>Q</m>,
                else <m>R</m> in logical notation.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    The statement says if <m>P</m>,
                    then <m>Q</m> and also if <m>\neg P</m>, then <m>R</m> so we have
                    <me>
                      (P \to Q) \land (\neg P \to R)
                    </me>
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Consider the following statement:
                for any integer <m>n</m>, if <m>n</m> is even,
                then the answer is <m>\frac{n}{2}</m>,
                else the answer is <m>3n+1</m>.
                What is the answer when <m>n=30</m>?
                What is the answer when <m>n = 7</m>?
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    When <m>n=30</m> the statement <m>n</m> is even is true and so the answer is <m>\frac{n}{2}=\frac{30}{2} = 15</m>.
                    On the other hand,
                    when <m>n=7</m> the statement <m>n</m> is even is false and so the answer is <m>3n+1 = 3(7)+1 = 22</m>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_pff_if_then">
    <title>\subpffifthen</title>
    <p>
      Since <m>P \to Q</m> promises that if <m>P</m> is true,
      then <m>Q</m> is true,
      our proof format begins by assuming that <m>P</m> is true and concludes once we have shown that <m>Q</m> is true.
      The proof does not mention the case where <m>P</m> is false since <m>P \to Q</m> is automatically true if that happens,
      as stated in <xref ref="rem_false_implies_is_true"></xref>.
    </p>
    <proof>
    <p>
      Prove: <m>P \to Q</m>
    </p>
    <proof>
      <p>
        Assume <m>P</m> is true.
      </p>
      <p>
        (Explain why it follows that <m>Q</m> is true.)
      </p>
      <p>
        Thus <m>Q</m> is true.
      </p>
    </proof>
    </proof>
    <p>
      As usual, when we introduce a new proof format,
      we present an example and ask you to edit it to prove a similar statement.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_pffifthen">
      <title>Direct proof of a conditional statement</title>
      <p>
        <nbsp/>
        <ol>
          <li xml:id="part_if_then_direct">
            <p>
              Copy the following proof of a direct proof of a conditional statement.
              Note that we are <xref ref="pff_forall">using</xref>
              because the statement is universally quantified as well <xref ref="pff_if_then_direct">as</xref>.
              Prove for any integer <m>m</m>,
              if <m>m</m> is odd then <m>3m</m> is odd.
              <proof>
                <p>
                  Let <m>m</m> be an integer.
                  Assume that <m>m</m> is odd.
                  By the definition of odd <xref ref="defn_even_odd"/> we can write <m>m=2k+1</m> for some integer <m>k</m>.
                  Then
                  <me>
                    3m=3(2k+1)=6k+3
                  </me>.
                </p>
                <p>
                  (Side note: to show that <m>3m</m> is odd,
                  we need to write <m>6k+3</m> in the form <m>2()+1</m>.)
                </p>
                <p>
                  Note that
                  <me>
                    6k+3 = 6k+2+1 = 2(3k+1) + 1
                  </me>.
                </p>
                <p>
                  Since <m>3k+1</m> is an integer,
                  it follows from the definition of odd that <m>3m</m> is odd.
                </p>
              </proof>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Edit the proof in <xref ref="part_if_then_direct"/> to prove that for any integer <m>m</m> if <m>m</m> is odd,
              then <m>5m</m> is odd.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_neg_conditional">
    <title>\subnegcond</title>
    <p>
      We have just seen how to prove that a conditional statement is true.
      How do we construct a counterexample involving a conditional statement to prove that it is false?
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_cex_conditionals">
      <title>Counterexamples involving conditional statements</title>
      <p>
        Show that each the statements (a)-(c) is false by finding a counterexample for each statement.
        <ol>
          <li xml:id="part_chromatic4_notK4">
            <p>
              If a graph has chromatic number four,
              then it must be the complete graph <m>K_4</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_cex_cond_xplusy">
            <p>
              Given real numbers <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>,
              if <m>x + y = 2</m>, then <m>x \le 1</m> and <m>y \le 1</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li xml:id="part_cex_cond_abmult6">
            <p>
              For any integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>,
              if <m>6 \mid ab</m>, then <m>6 \mid a</m> or <m>6 \mid b</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              What do we need to be true in order to show that <m>P \to Q</m> is false?
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Construct a truth table for <m>\neg (P \to Q)</m>.
              Include an intermediate column for <m>P \to Q</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\neg (P \to Q)</m> is logically equivalent to a statement involving <m>\land</m>.
              What is it?
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
      Make sure that you have <xref ref="act_cex_conditionals">completed</xref>
      because we are about to reveal the answers.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_cex_conditionals">
      <title>Counterexamples involving conditional statements</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          For each statement from <xref ref="act_cex_conditionals"></xref> (a)-(c),
          find a counterexample to show the statement is false.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                If a graph has chromatic number four,
                then it must be the complete graph <m>K_4</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    One possible counterexample is the wheel <m>W_5</m>,
                    drawn in <xref ref="fig_W4W5"></xref>.
                    (By the way,
                    we could not use <m>W_3</m> as a counterexample because <m>W_3 \cong K_4</m>.)
                    Notice that our counterexample has the hypothesis true and the conclusion false.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Given real numbers <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>,
                if <m>x + y = 2</m>, then <m>x \le 1</m> and <m>y \le 1</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    One possible counterexample is <m>x = 0.8</m> and <m>y=1.2</m>.
                    While it is true that <m>x=0.8 \le 1</m>,
                    because <m>y = 1.2 > 1</m> it follows that the conclusion that <m>x \le 1</m> and <m>y \le 1</m> is false.
                    Notice that our counterexample has the hypothesis true and the conclusion false.
                    To insure that the conclusion was false,
                    we used DeMorgan's Laws <xref ref="thm_demorgans"/> <m>\neg(P \land Q) \equiv \neg P \lor \neg Q</m>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                For any integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>,
                if <m>6 \mid ab</m>, then <m>6 \mid a</m> or <m>6 \mid b</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    One possible counterexample would be <m>a = 3</m> and <m>b = 4</m> because then <m>6 \mid 12 = ab</m> but
                    <m>6 \nmid 3</m> and <m>6 \nmid 4</m>.
                    Notice that our counterexample has the hypothesis true and the conclusion false.
                    To insure that the conclusion was false,
                    we used DeMorgan's Laws <xref ref="thm_demorgans"/> <m>\neg(P \lor Q) \equiv \neg P \land \neg Q</m>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      As we saw in <xref ref="act_cex_conditionals"></xref>
      and <xref ref="exam_cex_conditionals"></xref>,
      a counterexample to <m>P \to Q</m> must have <m>P</m> true and <m>Q</m> false.
      After all, that is the only way to break the promise.
    </p>
    <theorem xml:id="thm_broken_promise">
      <title>Broken promise</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The negation of
          <q>If <m>P</m>, then <m>Q</m></q>
          is the <term>broken promise</term>
          <q><m>P</m> but not <m>Q</m></q>. That is,
          <me>
            \neg(P \to Q) \equiv P \land \neg Q
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <p>
      Let's look at an example of writing the negation of conditional statements.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_neg_ifthen">
      <title>Negating conditional statements</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write the negation of each statement in a sentence.
          Hint: The negation should be true for your counterexample.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                If a graph has chromatic number four,
                then it must be the complete graph <m>K_4</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    Note that this statement does not state a specific quantifier,
                    so <xref ref="rem_default_universal">following</xref>,
                    we interpret this statement as universally quantified.
                    <xref ref="thm_neg_quants">Using</xref>
                    and <xref ref="thm_broken_promise"></xref>
                    we get the following negation: There exists a graph that has chromatic number four but is not the complete graph <m>K_4</m>.
                    Our counterexample from <xref ref="exam_cex_conditionals"></xref>
                    found a graph, namely <m>W_5</m>,
                    that has chromatic number four but is not the complete graph <m>K_4</m>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Given real numbers <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>,
                if <m>x + y = 2</m>, then <m>x \le 1</m> and <m>y \le 1</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We <xref ref="thm_neg_quants">use</xref>
                    and <xref ref="thm_broken_promise"></xref>
                    to find the following awkwardly-stated draft of the negation: There are real numbers <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> such that <m>x+y=2</m> but it is not the case that <m>x \le 1</m> and <m>y \le 1</m>.
                    We can eliminate the awkward
                    <q>it is not the case</q>
                    by using DeMorgan's law <xref ref="thm_demorgans"/>.
                    Our negation is the following statement: There are real numbers <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> such that <m>x+y=2</m> but either <m>x > 1</m> or <m>y > 1</m>.
                    Our counterexample from <xref ref="exam_cex_conditionals"></xref>
                    found real numbers <m>x = 0.8</m> and <m>y = 1.2</m> where <m>x+y=2</m> but <m>y > 1</m>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                For any integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>,
                if <m>6 \mid ab</m>, then <m>6 \mid a</m> or <m>6 \mid b</m>.
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We <xref ref="thm_neg_quants">use</xref>
                    and <xref ref="thm_broken_promise"></xref>
                    to find the following awkwardly-stated draft of the negation: There are integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> such that
                    <m>6 \mid ab</m> but it is not the case that <m>6 \mid a</m> or <m>6 \mid b</m>.
                    We can eliminate the awkward
                    <q>it is not the case</q>
                    by using DeMorgan's law <xref ref="thm_demorgans"/>.
                    Our negation is the following statement: There are integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> such that <m>6 \mid ab</m> but
                    <m>6 \nmid a</m> and <m>6 \nmid b</m>.
                    Our counterexample from <xref ref="exam_cex_conditionals"></xref>
                    found integers <m>a = 3</m> and <m>b = 4</m> where <m>6 \mid 12</m> but
                    <m>6 \nmid 3</m> and <m>6 \nmid 4</m>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="sub_pff_or_implication">
    <title>\subpfforimplication</title>
    <p>
      The implication equivalence <xref ref="thm_implication"/> gives us a new way to prove an
      <q>or</q>
      statement, which we saw earlier using cases in <xref ref="pff_or_by_cases"></xref>.
      That is, to prove <m>R \lor Q</m> we can prove <m>\neg R \to Q</m>.
    </p>
    <proof>
    <p>
      Prove: <m>R \lor Q</m>
    </p>
    <proof>
      <p>
        Assume <m>R</m> is false.
      </p>
      <p>
        (Explain why it follows that <m>Q</m> is true.)
      </p>
      <p>
        Thus <m>Q</m> is true.
      </p>
    </proof>
    </proof>
    <p>
      As usual, when we introduce a new proof format,
      we present an example and ask you to edit it to prove a similar statement.
    </p>
    <activity xml:id="act_pff_implication">
      <title>Direct proof of an
      <q>or</q>
      statement using an equivalent conditional</title>
      <p>
        <nbsp/>
        <ol>
          <li xml:id="part_or_implication">
            <p>
              Copy the following proof of proof of an
              <q>or</q>
              statement using the implication equivalence.
              Note that we are <xref ref="pff_forall">using</xref>
              because the statement is universally quantified as well <xref ref="pff_or_implication">as</xref>.
              Prove that for any positive real numbers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> such that <m>ab=100</m>,
              either <m>a \le 10</m> or <m>b \lt 10</m>.
              <proof>
                <p>
                  Let <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> be positive real numbers such that <m>ab = 100</m>.
                  Assume <m>a > 10</m>.
                  Multiplying each side of this equation by the positive number <m>b</m> we get <m>100=ab > 10b</m>.
                  Dividing each side of this equation by 10 we get <m>b \lt 10</m>.
                  Thus either <m>a \le 10</m> or <m>b \lt 10</m>.
                </p>
              </proof>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Edit the proof in <xref ref="part_or_implication"/> to prove that for any positive real numbers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> such that <m>ab=5</m>,
              either <m>a \le \sqrt{5}</m> or <m>b \lt \sqrt{5}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
      A common concern about proving an
      <q>or</q>
      statement using the implication equivalence is that we have proved that if <m>P</m> is false,
      then <m>Q</m> is true,
      but it feels like we are missing a proof that if <m>Q</m> is false,
      then <m>P</m> is true.
      It is not missing.
      Let's look at how to better <xref ref="pff_or_implication">understand</xref>
      by comparing it to proof by cases.
    </p>
    <example xml:id="exam_implication_vs_cases_proof_or">
      <title>Compare proving an
      <q>or</q>
      statement using implication versus proof by cases</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <nbsp/> <xref ref="pff_or_implication">Explain</xref>
          by considering how to prove
          <m>P \lor Q</m> using cases <xref ref="pff_or_by_cases"/> with the cases are <m>P</m> or <m>\neg P</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Prove: <m>P \lor Q</m> using cases <xref ref="pff_or_by_cases"/> with the cases <m>P</m> or <m>\neg P</m>.
        </p>
        <blockquote>
          <proof>
            <p>
              We consider two cases.
            </p>
            <p>
              Case 1: Assume <m>P</m>.
              Thus, <m>P</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
              Case 2: Assume <m>\neg P</m>.
              (Explain why <m>Q</m> follows.)
              Thus, <m>Q</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
              In either case, <m>P \lor Q</m>.
            </p>
          </proof>
        </blockquote>
        <p>
          When we cross out the obvious lines of the proof we get the following proof:
        </p>
        <blockquote>
          <proof>
            <p>
              \st{We consider two cases.}
            </p>
            <p>
              \st{Case 1: Assume <m>P</m>.
              Thus, <m>P</m>.}
            </p>
            <p>
              \st{Case 2:} Assume <m>\neg P</m>.
              (Explain why <m>Q</m> follows.)
              Thus, <m>Q</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
              \st{In either case, <m>P \lor Q</m>.}
            </p>
          </proof>
        </blockquote>
        <p>
          This proof is <xref ref="pff_or_implication">the</xref>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Exercises</title>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_if_then">for</xref> \subifthen</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_explain_cond_true">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Explain why each conditional statement is true.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  For any integer <m>k</m>, if <m>k=3</m>, then <m>2k+5 = 11</m>.
                  Hint: Plug in.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  For any integer <m>k</m>, if <m>2k+5 = 11</m>, then <m>k=3</m>.
                  Hint: Solve.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_verify_addition">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use a truth table to verify that <m>P \to (P \lor Q)</m> is a tautology.
            Include an intermediate column for <m>P \lor Q</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_truthtable_PimpliesnegQ">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Construct a truth table for <m>P \to \neg Q</m>.
                  Include an intermediate column for <m>\neg Q</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Construct a truth table for <m>Q \to \neg P</m>.
                  Include an intermediate column for <m>\neg P</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What do you notice?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_truthtable_mp">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Construct a truth table to show that <m>(P \land (P \to Q)) \to Q</m> is a tautology.
            This logical equivalence justifies <em>modus ponens</em>,
            a key logical inference we discuss in <xref ref="sec_inference"></xref>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_truthtable_compound_conditionals">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Construct a truth table for each statement.
            Include intermediate columns.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>P \to (Q \lor R)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>(P \to Q) \land (\neg P \to R)</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_truthtable_proof_cases">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Construct a truth table to show that
            <me>
              (P \to R) \land (Q \to R) \equiv (P \lor Q) \to R
            </me>.
            Include appropriate intermediate columns.
            This logical equivalence <xref ref="pff_cases">justifies</xref>
            (for 2 cases).
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_rewrite_implication">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Use the implication equivalence <xref ref="thm_implication"/> to rewrite the following statement as a conditional: Either you take a break from playing that video game or I will take away your controller for a week.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Use the implication equivalence <xref ref="thm_implication"/> to rewrite the following statement using
                  <q>or</q>: If you do not text me by 6 PM, then I will text you.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_iften">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What the symbol <m>\to</m> means in this logic context?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What the statement if <m>P</m>, then <m>Q</m> promises?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  When a conditional statement is true and when it is false?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to draw truth tables that involve conditional statements?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Why <m>P \to Q \equiv \neg P \lor Q</m>?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to use a truth table to verify that a logical equivalence is valid?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_equiv_PtoQtoR">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Is <m>P \lor (Q \to R)</m> logically equivalent to <m>(P \lor Q) \to R</m>?
            Use a truth table to justify your answer.
            Include appropriate intermediate columns.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_pff_if_then">for</xref> \subpffifthen</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_prove_cond_true">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <xref ref="pff_forall">Use</xref>
            and <xref ref="pff_if_then_direct"></xref>
            to prove each statement from <xref ref="exer_explain_cond_true"></xref>.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Prove for any integer <m>k</m>,
                  if <m>k=3</m>, then <m>2k+5 = 11</m>.
                  Hint: Plug in.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Prove for any integer <m>k</m>,
                  if <m>2k+5 = 11</m>, then <m>k=3</m>.
                  Hint: Solve.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_odd_sq_is_odd">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <xref ref="pff_forall">Use</xref>,
            <xref ref="pff_if_then_direct"></xref>,
            and <xref ref="defn_even_odd"></xref>
            to prove that for any integer <m>n</m>,
            if <m>n</m> is odd, then <m>n^2</m> is odd.
            Hint: Write <m>n=2k+1</m>.
            Next, simplify <m>n^2</m> and write it as <m>2(~)+1</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_mult6_is_mult3">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <xref ref="pff_forall">Use</xref>,
            <xref ref="pff_if_then_direct"></xref>,
            and <xref ref="defn_divides"></xref>
            to prove that for any integer <m>n</m>,
            if <m>6 \mid n</m>, then <m>3 \mid n</m>.
            Hint: Write <m>n = 6k</m> for some integer <m>k</m>.
            How can you write <m>n = 3(~)</m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_divides_square_proof">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/> <xref ref="pff_forall">Use</xref>,
            <xref ref="pff_if_then_direct"></xref>,
            and <xref ref="defn_divides"></xref> to prove if <m>a \mid b</m>,
            then <m>a \mid b^2</m> for any integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.
            Hint: Write <m>b = ak</m> for some integer <m>k</m>.
            Next, simplify <m>b^2</m> and write it as <m>a(~)</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_proof_sums_prod_even_odd">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/> <xref ref="pff_forall">Use</xref>,
            <xref ref="pff_and"></xref>,
            and <xref ref="pff_if_then_direct"></xref>
            to prove for any integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> if <m>a</m> is even and <m>b</m> is odd,
            then <m>a+b</m> is odd and <m>ab</m> is even.
            Hint: Write <m>a = 2k_1</m> and
            <m>b = 2k_2+1</m> for some integers <m>k_1</m> and <m>k_2</m>.
            (You cannot use the same integer <m>k</m> for both.)
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_divides_transitive">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/> <xref ref="pff_forall">Use</xref>,
            <xref ref="pff_if_then_direct"></xref>,
            and <xref ref="defn_divides"></xref>
            to prove that if <m>a \mid b</m> and <m>b \mid c</m>,
            then <m>a \mid c</m> for any integers <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>,
            and <m>c</m>.
            Hint: Write <m>b=ak_1</m> and <m>c=bk_2</m> for some integers <m>k_1</m> and <m>k_2</m>.
            You cannot use the same integer <m>k</m> for both.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_pffifthen">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Why we only need to consider when <m>P</m> is true when proving <m>P \to Q</m>?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What we assume at the beginning of the direct proof that <m>P \to Q</m>?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to prove <m>P \to Q</m> directly?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_last_digit_even_odd">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Prove that for any integer <m>n</m> and digit <m>s</m> that if <m>s</m> is even,
            then <m>10n+s</m> is even and if <m>s</m> is odd, then <m>10n+s</m> is odd.
            <xref ref="pff_forall">Use</xref>,
            <xref ref="pff_and"></xref>,
            <xref ref="pff_if_then_direct"></xref>,
            and <xref ref="defn_even_odd"></xref>.
          </p>
          <p>
            It follows from this exercise that if the last digit of an integer is even,
            then that integer is even and if the last digit of an integer is odd,
            then that integer is odd.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_proof_EAthm_recursion">
        <title>\exerE</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            In this exercise,
            we <xref ref="thm_Euclidean_algorithm">prove</xref>
            <xref ref="part_EAthm_recursion"/>.
            Let <m>a</m>, <m>n</m>, <m>q</m>,
            and <m>r</m> be integers such that <m>a = nq + r</m>.
            (We are most interested in the case where <m>r = a</m> <c>mod</c> <m>n</m>,
            but the result holds in general.)
            <ol>
              <li xml:id="part_EAthm_implies">
                <p>
                  <xref ref="pff_forall">Use</xref>,
                  <xref ref="pff_if_then_direct"></xref>,
                  and <xref ref="defn_divides"></xref>
                  to prove that for any integer <m>d</m>,
                  if <m>d \mid n</m> and <m>d \mid r</m>, then <m>d \mid a</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What does <xref ref="part_EAthm_implies"/> tell you is true about any common divisor of <m>n</m> and <m>r</m>?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li xml:id="part_EAthm_converse">
                <p>
                  <xref ref="pff_forall">Use</xref>,
                  <xref ref="pff_if_then_direct"></xref>,
                  and <xref ref="defn_divides"></xref>
                  to prove that for any integer <m>d</m>,
                  if <m>d \mid a</m> and <m>d \mid n</m>, then <m>d \mid r</m>.
                  Hint: Solve for <m>r</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What does <xref ref="part_EAthm_converse"/> tell you is true about any common divisor of <m>a</m> and <m>n</m>?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li xml:id="part_EAthm_commondivs">
                <p>
                  Explain why it follows from <xref ref="part_EAthm_implies"/> and <xref ref="part_EAthm_converse"/> that the list of common divisors of <m>a</m> and <m>n</m> is the same as the list of common divisors of <m>n</m> and <m>r</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Explain why it follows from <xref ref="part_EAthm_commondivs"/> that <c>gcd</c><m>(a,n) =</m> <c>gcd</c> <m>(n,r)</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_neg_conditional">for</xref> \subnegcond</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_cex_graphs_cond">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Each of the following statements is false.
            Find a counterexample to each statement.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  If a graph contains a 5-cycle, then contains a 4-cycle.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  If two graphs <m>G</m> and <m>H</m> have the same degree sequence,
                  then they are isomorphic.
                  Hint: Try 3-regular graph with six vertices.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  For any vertices <m>v</m> and <m>w</m> in the path <m>P_6</m>,
                  if <m>v</m> and <m>w</m> are adjacent,
                  then <m>v</m> and <m>w</m> have the same degree.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_truthtable_neg_conditional">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Use a truth table to verify the equivalence in <xref ref="thm_broken_promise"></xref>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_product_divides12">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Each of the following statements is false.
            Find a counterexample to each statement.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  For any integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>,
                  if <m>a \mid 12</m> and <m>b \mid 12</m>, then <m>ab \mid 12</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  For any integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>,
                  if <m>12 \mid ab</m>, then <m>12 \mid a</m> or <m>12 \mid b</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_negation_ifthen_graphs">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <xref ref="thm_broken_promise">Use</xref>
            to write the negation of each statement in a sentence.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  If a graph contains a 5-cycle, then contains a 4-cycle.
                  Note that by <xref ref="rem_default_universal"></xref>,
                  this statement is universally quantified so <xref ref="thm_neg_quants">use</xref>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  If two graphs <m>G</m> and <m>H</m> have the same degree sequence,
                  then they are isomorphic.
                  Again, <xref ref="thm_neg_quants">use</xref>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  For any vertices <m>v</m> and <m>w</m> in the path <m>P_6</m>,
                  if <m>v</m> and <m>w</m> are adjacent,
                  then <m>v</m> and <m>w</m> have the same degree.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_negation_ifthen_even">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Each of the following statements is false.
            First, find a counterexample and then <xref ref="thm_broken_promise">use</xref>
            to write the negation of each statement in a sentence.
            Hint: Use DeMorgan's laws <xref ref="thm_demorgans"/>.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  For any integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>,
                  if <m>a+b</m> is even, then <m>a</m> is even or <m>b</m> is even.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  For any integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>,
                  if <m>ab</m> is even, then <m>a</m> is even and <m>b</m> is even.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_neg_conditional">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to use the idea of a broken promise to find a counterexample to <m>P \to Q</m>?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  What the negation of <m>P \to Q</m> is?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title>Exercises <xref ref="sub_pff_or_implication">for</xref> \subpfforimplication</title>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_integer_or_next_is_even">
        <title>\exerP</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Consider the following statement <m>S</m>: For any integer <m>n</m>,
            either <m>n</m> is even or <m>n+1</m> is even.
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <xref ref="thm_implication">Use</xref>
                  to rewrite <m>S</m> as a conditional statement without the word
                  <q>or</q>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <xref ref="pff_forall">Use</xref>
                  and <xref ref="pff_or_implication"></xref> to prove <m>S</m>.
                  Recall that if <m>n</m> is not even, then <m>n</m> is odd.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_no_zd_integers">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/>
            <ol>
              <li xml:id="part_equiv_or_conclusion">
                <p>
                  Use a truth table to verify that
                  <m>P \to (Q \lor R)</m> is equivalent to <m>(P \land \neg Q) \to R</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li xml:id="part_zd_without_or">
                <p>
                  Consider the following conditional statement <m>S</m>: For any integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>,
                  if <m>ab=0</m>, then <m>a=0</m> or <m>b=0</m>.
                  Use <xref ref="part_equiv_or_conclusion"/> to rewrite <m>S</m> without
                  <q>or</q>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_proof_no_zd_integers">
        <title>\exerU</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            <nbsp/> Consider the following conditional statement <m>S</m> from <xref ref="exer_no_zd_integers"></xref>: For any integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>,
            if <m>ab=0</m>, then <m>a=0</m> or <m>b=0</m>.
            <xref ref="pff_forall">Use</xref>,
            <xref ref="pff_if_then_direct"></xref>,
            and <xref ref="pff_or_implication"></xref> to prove <m>S</m>.
            Hint: if <m>a \neq 0</m>,
            then you may divide each side of the equation <m>ab=0</m> by <m>a</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="exer_dyk_pfforimplication">
        <title>\exerR</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do you know <ellipsis/>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  How to prove <m>P \lor Q</m> using the implication equivalence?
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Why we only need to consider when <m>P</m> is false when proving <m>P \lor Q</m>?
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Select Answers and Hints</title>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_explain_cond_true"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            When <m>k=3</m> we have <m>2k+5 = 2(3) + 5 = 11</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Now explain how to solve the equation.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_verify_addition"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: The truth table should have four columns:
        <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, <m>P \lor Q</m>, <m>P \to (P \lor Q)</m>.
        The truth table should also have four rows,
        as in <xref ref="exam_truthtable_conditionals"></xref>.
        To show that the statement is a tautology,
        the last column of your truth table should be all <c>T</c> s.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_truthtable_proof_cases"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: Your truth table should have eight columns:
        <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, <m>R</m>,
        <m>P \to R</m>, <m>Q \to R</m>,
        <m>(P \to R) \land (Q \to R)</m>, <m>P \lor Q</m>,
        and <m>(P \lor Q) \to R</m>.
        Your truth table should also have eight rows,
        as in <xref ref="exam_distributive_equiv"></xref>.
        The sixth and eighth columns should be the same.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_rewrite_implication"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            If you do not take a break from playing that video game,
            then I will take away your controller for a week.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Your answer should not have any negative words
            (like
            <q>not</q>).
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_mult6_is_mult3"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: The proof begins
      </p>
      <blockquote>
        <em>Proof.</em>  Let <m>n</m> be an integer.  Assume <m>6 \mid n</m>.  By definition of divides, \ldots
      </blockquote>
      <p>
        Then use the hint.
      </p>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_proof_sums_prod_even_odd"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: Here is an outline of the proof.
      </p>
      <blockquote>
        <em>Proof.</em>  Let <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> be integers.  Assume \ldots.
        By the definitions of even and odd, we can write \ldots (use hint)
        Then, first, <m>a+b=</m> \ldots. Thus, \ldots.
        Next, <m>ab =</m> \ldots. Thus, \ldots.
      </blockquote>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_divides_transitive"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <blockquote>
        <em>Proof.</em>  Let <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m> be integers.  Assume <m>a \mid b</m> and <m>b \mid c</m>. By the definitions of divides, we can write <m>b=ak_1</m> and <m>c=bk_2</m> for some integers <m>k_1</m> and <m>k_2</m>. Then,
        <me>
          c = bk_2 = (ak_1)k_2 = a(k_1k_2) = ak
        </me>
        where <m>k = k_1k_2</m> is an integer.  Thus, by definition of divides, <m>a \mid c</m>.  <m>\Box</m>
      </blockquote>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_last_digit_even_odd"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <p>
        Hint: Here is an outline of the proof.
      </p>
      <blockquote>
        <em>Proof.</em>  Let <m>n</m> be an integer and let <m>s</m> be a digit.
        First, assume <m>s</m> is even.  By definition of even we can write <m>s=</m> \ldots.  Then
        <me>
          10n+s = \ldots = 2k'
        </me>
        where <m>k' = \ldots</m> is an integer.  Thus <m>10n+s</m> is even.
        Next, assume <m>s</m> is odd.  By definition of odd we can write <m>s=</m> \ldots.  Then
        <me>
          10n+s = \ldots = 2k'+1
        </me>
        where <m>k' = \ldots</m> is an integer.  Thus <m>10n+s</m> is odd.
      </blockquote>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_cex_graphs_cond"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Your graph should contain a 5-cycle.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Your graphs should not be isomorphic.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: To show the counterexample,
            draw <m>P_6</m> and label two of the vertices <m>v</m> and <m>w</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_product_divides12"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: One possible counterexample is <m>a = 6</m> and <m>b = 4</m>.
            Try to find a different counterexample.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Check that your counterexample has <m>12 \mid ab</m>,
            <m>12 \nmid a</m>, and <m>12 \nmid b</m>.
            (We used DeMorgan's laws.)
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_negation_ifthen_graphs"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            There is a graph that contains a 5-cycle but does not contain a 4-cycle.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Your negation should not include the word
            <q>if</q>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Your negation should not include the word
            <q>if</q>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
    <subsubsection>
      <title><xref ref="exer_negation_ifthen_even"></xref> Select Answers and Hints</title>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            For some integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>,
            <m>a+b</m> is even, but <m>a</m> is odd and <m>b</m> is odd.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Hint: Make sure you understand how we got the answer to part (a).
            Your negation should not include the words
            <q>if</q>
            or
            <q>and</q>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>
  </subsection>
</section>